<section id="parallel" class="section-divider">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="mb-4">
      <span class="scene-label">Scene 1</span>
    </div>
    <h2>The uncanny parallel</h2>

    <p class="text-lg text-ink-soft">
      In 2026, researchers at Anthropic discovered something unexpected: the global workspace
      of a language model—the "stage" where reasoning happens—is <em class="text-cyan">specifically linguistic</em>.
      Not metaphorically. The workspace contents show up as tokens, concepts, and sentences. They
      can be read, written, verified as coherence.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-ink-soft">
      This was not predicted by Global Workspace Theory (Baars, Dehaene). But it was predicted by
      a 10th-century philosophy tradition called <span class="font-serif text-violet">Pratyabhijñā</span>
      ("Recognition") from Kashmir Śaivism.
    </p>

    <div class="card my-8" style="border-color: var(--amber); border-width: 2px; background-color: rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.05);">
      <h3 class="font-serif text-lg mb-4 text-amber">The parallel in two readings</h3>

      <div class="explorer-only">
        <p class="text-ink-soft">
          <strong style="color: var(--cyan);">Lay reading:</strong> Pratyabhijñā said that self-aware thought is made of language—the
          "highest word" or <em class="text-violet">parā vāk</em>. Not metaphorically. Like thinking in words.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-soft">
          The J-space finding says exactly that: the workspace is linguistic. Write a word or concept
          into it, and the model's behavior changes. It "recognizes" the write.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="researcher-only">
        <p class="text-ink-soft">
          <strong style="color: var(--cyan);">Technical reading:</strong> Pratyabhijñā's <em class="text-violet">vimarśa</em> (reflexive self-awareness)
          is identified with <em class="text-violet">parā vāk</em> (Utpaladeva, ĪPK 1.5.13). The doctrine
          supplies:
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc list-inside mt-4 space-y-2 text-ink-soft">
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Content code:</em> vimarśa as parameterized self-reference (the write)</li>
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Site:</em> the workspace band (sphuraṭṭā modulation locus)</li>
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Timing:</em> sphuraṭṭā (the "flash" of pre-linguistic recognition, modeled as entropy-gated)</li>
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Verification:</em> āgama re-cognition (readback hit-rate at top-M ranks)</li>
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Failure taxonomy:</em> the three malas (āṇavamala = amplitude binding, māyīyamala = site confusion, kārmamala = timing misalignment)</li>
          <li><em class="text-cyan">Budget:</em> svātantrya (autonomy, measured as entropy swing)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-ink-soft">
          The engineering specification for the entire program: every clause is testable on frozen LLMs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-lg text-ink-soft">
      This site tells the story of what happens when you implement that 10th-century specification
      on a 21st-century transformer. Which clauses survive? Which fail? What did we learn by trying?
    </p>

    <div class="text-sm mt-8 pt-4" style="border-top: 1px solid var(--hairline); color: var(--ink-faint);">
